<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="44" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[264,1325,1330,1556]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">
Recorded across 
<collectingCountry box="[515,603,1330,1356]" name="Canada" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">Canada</collectingCountry>
from the Northwest Territories east to Nova 
<collectingCountry box="[1144,1217,1330,1356]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">Scotia</collectingCountry>
with the exception of Saskatchewan (
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell" box="[620,828,1370,1396]" pageId="7" pageNumber="49" refString="Campbell, J. M. (1991 d) Family Pyrochroidae: fire-coloured beetles. In: Bousquet, Y. (Ed.). Checklist of the Beetles of Canada and Alaska. Agriculture Canada Publication 1861 / E. pp. 269." type="journal article" year="1991" yearSuffix="d">
Campbell 
<number box="[751,813,1370,1396]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="1991.0">1991</number>
d
</bibRefCitation>
); scattered distribution in the Maritime Provinces (
<figureCitation box="[395,467,1410,1436]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[264,368,1058,1082]" captionTargetBox="[444,1142,479,1046]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[440,1147,474,1047]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distribution of Dendroides concolor and Neopyrochroa femoralis in the Maritime Provinces of Canada." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173001/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">
Fig. 
<number box="[450,467,1410,1436]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). In the 
<collectingCountry box="[562,718,1410,1436]" name="United States of America" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">United States</collectingCountry>
from Maine south to Maryland and west to Illinois, Wisconsin, Minnesota, and South Dakota (
<bibRefCitation author="Downie" box="[778,1064,1450,1476]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" refString="Downie, N. M. &amp; Arnett, R. H., Jr. (1996) The beetles of northeastern North America. Sandhill Crane Press, Gainesville, Florida. 1721 pp." type="book" year="1996">
Downie &amp; Arnett 
<number box="[1001,1064,1450,1476]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae are found in decaying woody sections of moss­covered logs in boreal­like areas (e.g. edges of bogs) (
<bibRefCitation author="Young" box="[272,422,1530,1556]" pageId="7" pageNumber="51" refString="Young, D. A. (2002) Pyrochroidae Latreille 1807. In: Arnett, R. H., Jr., Thomas, M. C., Skelley, P. E. &amp; Frank, J. H. (Eds.). American Beetles, Volume 2: Polyphaga: Scarabaeoidea through Curculionoidea. CRC Press, Boca Raton, USA. pp. 540 - 543." type="journal article" year="2002">
Young 
<number box="[358,422,1530,1556]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
